Here are both approaches for navigating from `ProductListPage` to `ProductDetailsPage`:

## 1. Register the Route

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
public AppShell()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
}
```

## 2. Navigate — String Parameter (query string)

```csharp
// In ProductListViewModel or code-behind
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

## 3. Navigate — Full Object (ShellNavigationQueryParameters)

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
}
```

## 4. Receive Data with IQueryAttributable

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _productId;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach 2: full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ApplyQueryAttributes` handles both cases — query-string values arrive as `object` (boxed strings), complex objects arrive as their actual type.
- Always `await` `GoToAsync`.
- Set the ViewModel as `BindingContext` on `ProductDetailsPage` (via DI or in code-behind).
